^c@2^Y@3In the rule just given, it was specified that to play your highest card you must not have the card directly below it in rank. There was a reason for this. If you do have two or more high cards of Partner's led suit, and these are in sequence, you should not play the highest card, but the lowest card of the sequence. This is true for any number of cards in unbroken sequence at the top of the led suit. If you hold Ace-King, you play the |cp|8|at|King|cp||at|; if you hold King-Queen, you play the |cp|8|at|Queen|cp||at|; if you hold King-Queen-Jack, you play the |cp|8|at|Jack|cp||at|; if you hold K Q J 10, you play the |cp|8|at|Ten|cp||at|. |
